{"sections":[],"metadata":{"role":"article","modules":[{"name":"EmacsSwiftModule"}],"roleHeading":"Article","title":"Defining Lisp Functions"},"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Defining Emacs Lisp functions directly from Swift."}],"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"text":"defun","anchor":"defun","level":2,"type":"heading"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" provides many overloads of the "},{"code":"defun","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" method allowing you to convert Swift functions to Lisp functions."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"All the variants take 3 arguments:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"optional name for a new function (","type":"text"},{"code":"nil","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" for lambda)"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"docstring (empty by default)"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"function implementation as a Swift closure","type":"text"}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"It returns an opaque "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsValue","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" that can be called via ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"funcall"},{"text":" or ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"apply"},{"type":"text","text":" (mostly useful for lambda functions)."},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"If something goes wrong on the Emacs side, it can throw "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError"},{"type":"text","text":", however, it is much less likely compared to calls."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Let’s start with this simple example to see how it works:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["env.defun(\"swift-+\") { (lhs: Int, rhs: Int) -> Int in lhs + rhs }"]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This will define a Lisp function named "},{"code":"swift-+","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" taking exactly two arguments. You can call it like any other Lisp function."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["(swift-+ 1 1) ;; => 2"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"emacs-lisp"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If you pass not integers as arguments, you get "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"wrong-type-argument"},{"type":"text","text":" like with any other Lisp function expecting certain types from its arguments."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You can use any type that is convertible to Lisp (see "},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/TypeConversions","type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":") as your closure argument\/return types to get this sweet automatic conversion."}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Acquiring the Environment","anchor":"Acquiring-the-Environment"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Our ","type":"text"},{"code":"swift-+","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" function is nice, but we don’t communicate with Emacs internals in it, while in the majority of cases we’d want to call a thing or two from the Lisp side. Since our code is a closure, we might have a temptation to simply capture the "},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment","type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" variable and use it. DON’T DO THAT. See more on the reasons in "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Lifetimes","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":", but for now just remember to add it as a parameter into your closure."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["env.defun(\"swift-+\") {","  (env: Environment, lhs: Int, rhs: Int) throws -> Int in","  try env.funcall(\"+\", with: lhs, rhs)","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This new version still can be called exactly the same way, but now it calls a Lisp function itself.","type":"text"}]},{"style":"important","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Don’t capture environment in your function’s body. If you need it, add it as a first parameter of your closure."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"name":"Important","type":"aside"},{"anchor":"Using-Opaque-Values","text":"Using Opaque Values","type":"heading","level":2},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Sometimes we don’t want to use a fancy conversion in our function and we simply want to forward our dynamically typed argument to another Lisp function. This is totally valid and we can use "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsValue","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"text":" directly in our function’s signature.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"swift","code":["env.defun(\"to-string\") {","  (env: Environment, value: EmacsValue) throws -> String in","  try env.funcall(\"format\", with: \"%S\", value)","}"],"type":"codeListing"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This function takes an opaque value and forwards it to another function. We re-throw any exceptions coming from that call, so if that function has some type expectation for it’s argument, the user still gets notified about it.","type":"text"}]},{"name":"Important","type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Opaque values have very specific lifetime rules to them. Please, check ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Lifetimes","isActive":true},{"text":" for more detail.","type":"text"}]}],"style":"important"}]}],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/DefiningLispFunctions","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"minor":3,"patch":0},"variants":[{"paths":["\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/defininglispfunctions"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"kind":"article","seeAlsoSections":[{"title":"Getting started","generated":true,"identifiers":["doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/DefiningAModule","doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/CallingLispFunctions","doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/TypeConversions","doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/ErrorHandling"]}],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule"],["doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule","doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment"]]},"references":{"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/DefiningAModule":{"title":"Defining a module","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Defining a new Emacs module from Swift."}],"role":"article","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/definingamodule","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/DefiningAModule","type":"topic","kind":"article"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/Environment":{"type":"topic","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"class"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"identifier","text":"Environment"}],"role":"symbol","kind":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/environment","title":"Environment","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"Environment","kind":"identifier"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Environment is the interaction point with Emacs. If you want to do anything on the Emacs side, you need to have an Environment."}]},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/EmacsError":{"abstract":[{"text":"The main type representing Emacs errors.","type":"text"}],"title":"EmacsError","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"enum"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"identifier","text":"EmacsError"}],"type":"topic","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"EmacsError","kind":"identifier"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError","role":"symbol","kind":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/emacserror"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/TypeConversions":{"abstract":[{"text":"Converting Swift values into Lisp values and vice versa.","type":"text"}],"title":"Type conversions","type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/TypeConversions","role":"article","kind":"article","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/typeconversions"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/CallingLispFunctions":{"role":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Calling Lisp functions from your Swift code."}],"type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/CallingLispFunctions","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/callinglispfunctions","title":"Calling Lisp Functions","kind":"article"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/EmacsValue":{"fragments":[{"text":"class","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"EmacsValue","kind":"identifier"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsValue","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/emacsvalue","navigatorTitle":[{"kind":"identifier","text":"EmacsValue"}],"title":"EmacsValue","role":"symbol","type":"topic","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"An opaque Emacs value representing something from the Emacs Lisp world."}],"kind":"symbol"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/Lifetimes":{"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/lifetimes","role":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Lifetimes","abstract":[{"text":"Emacs internals lifetimes.","type":"text"}],"kind":"article","title":"Lifetimes","type":"topic"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/ErrorHandling":{"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/errorhandling","role":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/ErrorHandling","abstract":[{"text":"Handling Lisp errors on Swift side and vice versa.","type":"text"}],"kind":"article","title":"Error Handling","type":"topic"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule":{"role":"collection","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"A Swift library to write Emacs plugins in Swift!"}],"type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule","title":"EmacsSwiftModule","kind":"symbol"}}}